        weight: "high",
        info: "<p><strong>PAgP desirable mode</strong> configures a port to <strong>actively initiate PAgP negotiation</strong>. A desirable port sends PAgP frames as soon as the link comes up, trying to form a channel with the partner. Command: <code>channel-group N mode desirable</code>.</p><p><strong>LACP equivalent:</strong> <strong>desirable = active</strong>. Both modes mean 'I will initiate.' The semantic is identical; only the protocol (PAgP vs LACP) and the word used differ. If you understand LACP active, you understand PAgP desirable.</p><p><strong>Rule:</strong> for a PAgP channel to form, <strong>at least one side must be desirable</strong>. Exactly parallel to 'at least one side must be active' in LACP. Two sides in auto mode will never form a channel because neither will initiate.</p><p><strong>Configuration example:</strong></p><pre>! Switch A (Cisco only)\ninterface range Gi0/1 - 2\n channel-group 1 mode desirable\n!\n! Switch B (Cisco only)\ninterface range Gi0/1 - 2\n channel-group 1 mode desirable</pre><p>Both sides desirable is the PAgP equivalent of both sides active — the fastest and most robust PAgP combination.</p><p><strong>Verification:</strong> <code>show etherchannel summary</code> shows protocol 'PAgP' and members as (P) when bundled. <code>show pagp neighbor</code> shows the partner's info.</p>",
