        id: "2.4.c.6",
        term: "Mode mapping LACP ↔ PAgP",
        weight: "high",
        info: "<p>LACP and PAgP are conceptually identical — same two-mode structure, same 'at least one initiator' rule. The exam tests whether you know the mapping between the two protocols' mode names.</p><p><strong>The mapping:</strong></p><ul><li><strong>LACP active ≡ PAgP desirable</strong> — both actively initiate negotiation frames</li><li><strong>LACP passive ≡ PAgP auto</strong> — both only respond; never initiate</li></ul><p><strong>Memory trick:</strong> 'DA = PA.' <strong>D</strong>esirable = <strong>A</strong>ctive. <strong>A</strong>uto = <strong>P</strong>assive. Or alphabetically: 'Active-Desirable, Passive-Auto' — both pairs go together.</p><p><strong>Critical rule: protocols CANNOT be mixed.</strong> If Switch A uses LACP (active or passive) and Switch B uses PAgP (desirable or auto), the channel <strong>does not form</strong>. The two sides send different negotiation frames and don't understand each other. Both sides must use the same protocol family:</p><ul><li>Both LACP (active/passive) — works if at least one is active</li><li>Both PAgP (desirable/auto) — works if at least one is desirable</li><li>Both static (mode on) — works</li><li>Any mix of protocols — fails</li></ul><p><strong>Common scenario:</strong> an engineer inherits a Cisco switch with PAgP and replaces the partner switch with a non-Cisco switch. The new partner is configured with LACP because that's all it supports. The channel won't form on either side until the Cisco switch is changed from PAgP to LACP.</p>",
